<body><div class=WordSection1>
<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>🤖 AI001 Week 4 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Breaking It Into Steps · <strong>Course:</strong> AI Coding with Replit Agent · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>If you ask the AI to build a whole app in one giant prompt, it loses focus and the result is sloppy. This week you learn to go <strong>first → then → finally</strong>. Each step is its own prompt, and the AI builds on top of the last result.</p>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each plan. Before the AI builds it, write what you think the result will be like.</p>
<pre><code>[One prompt]
&quot;Build a complete to-do app with adding, deleting,
checking off tasks, saving, dark mode, and animations.&quot;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>This asks for everything at once. What might come out messy or missing?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code>[Step 1]
&quot;Build a basic to-do screen: an input box, an 'Add' button,
and an empty list.&quot;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>This is just the first step. What is NOT here yet? Is that okay?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code>[Step 2]
&quot;Now make the 'Add' button put the input text into the list.&quot;
[Step 3]
&quot;Add an 'X' next to each item that deletes it.&quot;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Why is building Step 2 then Step 3 easier than asking for both at once?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Weak Plan 🐛</h2>
<p>Each plan below has a step problem. Read what the student <strong>wanted</strong>, then rewrite the steps in a better order or split them up. Then explain the fix.</p>
<p><strong>Plan A</strong> — The steps are in the <strong>wrong order</strong>: it tries to delete items before any list exists.</p>
<pre><code>[Step 1] &quot;Add a delete button to each item.&quot;
[Step 2] &quot;Make a screen with an input box and an empty list.&quot;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> you cannot delete from a list that is not built yet.</p>
<p><strong>Write the steps in the right order:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was the order wrong?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Plan B</strong> — This "step" is actually <strong>five things crammed into one</strong> prompt.</p>
<pre><code>[Step 1] &quot;Add the list, the delete button, the checkbox,
dark mode, and a save feature.&quot;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> split it into separate steps, one feature each.</p>
<p><strong>Write it as separate steps:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why is one-feature-per-step better?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Plan C</strong> — The student forgot the <strong>very first step</strong>: there is no basic screen to build on.</p>
<pre><code>[Step 1] &quot;Make the add button add text to the list.&quot;
[Step 2] &quot;Add a delete button.&quot;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> what has to exist before an 'add' button can work?</p>
<p><strong>Write a Step 0 that goes first:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why does the screen need to come first?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Build an App in Steps 📸</h2>
<p>Pick a <strong>simple app idea</strong> (a to-do list, a score counter, a flashcard page — your choice). Plan it as <strong>4 to 5 steps</strong>, then run each step as its own prompt in Replit.</p>
<p>When you finish, send a <strong>photo or video</strong> of the final app, then explain what you did. Use these sentence starters — write 4 to 6 sentences total.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>My app idea was …</p>
<p>My first step built …</p>
<p>My next steps added …</p>
<p>Building one step at a time helped because …</p>
<p>One step I had to redo was …</p>
<p>If I had more time, I would …</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Write Out Your Steps 🗒️</h2>
<p>Write your <strong>4 to 5 step prompts</strong> in order, word for word. You will submit these with your app.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Step 1:</p>
<p>Step 2:</p>
<p>Step 3:</p>
<p>Step 4:</p>
<p>Step 5 (if you have one):</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h3>Submit ✅</h3>
<p>Send this worksheet + a photo (or video) of your app + your step-by-step prompts to teacher on KakaoTalk.</p>
<div class="footer">영어코딩 · <b>english-coding.co.uk</b></div>
</div></body></html>
